Upon the formation or acquisition of any direct or indirect Material Subsidiary after the Effective Date, the Borrower must, within thirty days, take the following actions:

(a) Cause the newly formed or acquired Material Subsidiary to provide a joinder to the agreement, becoming a co-borrower, along with appropriate financing statements and/or Control Agreements, in form and substance satisfactory to the Bank, ensuring the Bank obtains a first-priority lien (subject to Permitted Liens) in the assets of the subsidiary;

(b) Provide the Bank with appropriate certificates, powers, and financing statements pledging all direct or beneficial ownership interests in the new Material Subsidiary, in form and substance satisfactory to the Bank;

(c) Supply all other documentation, as determined by the Bank to be appropriate for the execution and delivery of the documents referenced above.

Additionally, the Borrower must execute any further instruments and take further action as the Bank reasonably requests to perfect or continue its lien in the Collateral or to achieve the purposes of the agreement.

The Assumed Liabilities include:

(a) All liabilities of Sellers under the Assumed Contracts that become due from and after the Closing Date, excluding any liabilities arising from pre-Closing breaches, defaults, or misrepresentations by Sellers, unless cured by the payment of Cure Costs;

(b) All cure costs required to be paid under section 365 of the Bankruptcy Code in connection with the assumption and assignment of the Assumed Contracts;

(c) All liabilities arising from the conduct of the Acquired Business or the ownership of the Acquired Assets by the Buyer from and after the Closing Date;

(d) All liabilities agreed to be assumed by the Buyer or for which the Buyer has agreed to be responsible under the agreement.

The Sellers are obligated to conduct the business of the Company in the ordinary course of business consistent with past practice and to use reasonable best efforts to maintain and preserve the current organization, business, and franchise of the Company. They must also preserve the rights, franchises, goodwill, and relationships with employees, customers, lenders, suppliers, regulators, and others having business relationships with the Company. Additionally, they must:

- Preserve and properly maintain all Licenses;
- Maintain and protect the properties and assets owned, operated, or used by the Company in the same condition as they were on the date of the Agreement, subject to reasonable wear and tear;
- Not amend, or allow the Company to amend, any Contract;
- Ensure the Company complies with all applicable Laws.

These obligations are to be fulfilled from the date of the Agreement until the Closing, except as otherwise provided in the Agreement or consented to in writing by the Buyer.

The Major Decisions that require the consent of the Sponsor Member (or, if replaced, the MGP Member) include:

(a) Causing a Property Disposition prior to the Lockout Date;  
(b) Causing a Property Disposition on or after the Lockout Date without complying with Section 6.12, to the extent required;  
(c) Acquiring any real property or material tangible personal property;  
(d) Electing to dissolve, liquidate, and/or terminate the Company under Section 8.2(a);  
(e) Instituting or consenting to a Bankruptcy of the Company or any Subsidiary of the Company;  
(f) Entering into any Credit Arrangements other than the Initial Financing, or amending, supplementing, or otherwise modifying the terms of any Credit Arrangements, or making or giving any material notices or elections to the lender under any Credit Arrangement (excluding ordinary course reporting and required deliverables, with written notice to the other Member unless directly received);  
(g) Admitting any Member to the Company other than in accordance with Section 7.5;  
(h) Effecting a change in any tax or accounting policies adopted;  
(m) Causing the Company to enter into, or grant any consent or approval of, any transaction with an Affiliate of the Managing Member (or Sponsor Member if the Managing Member is a Third Party appointed by Sponsor Member), unless the transaction is (i) contemplated by this Agreement, the MTA, or related documents, or (ii) on terms no less favorable than an arm’s length, market-rate transaction with an unaffiliated third party, with prompt written notice to the other Member;  
(n) Approving or consenting to any change in management of a Property at any time after the Lease is terminated;  
(o) Taking any other matter or action subject to the consent of the Sponsor Member (or MGP Member) as expressly set forth in the Agreement;  
(p) Extending credit, making loans (other than ordinary course expense advances to directors or officers), or making, executing, or delivering on behalf of the Company any material indemnity or surety bond, or obligating the Company as a surety or guarantor.
